Kubernetes Probes Notes
What are Probes in Kubernetes

In Kubernetes, Probes are used to check the health and status of containers.

Kubernetes uses probes to determine:

Whether the application is alive

Whether the application is ready to accept traffic

Whether the application has started successfully

There are three types of probes in Kubernetes:

Liveness Probe

Readiness Probe

Startup Probe

1. Liveness Probe

A Liveness Probe checks whether the container is running or not.

If the application becomes unresponsive or crashes, Kubernetes restarts the container automatically.

Example YAML
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: liveness-pod
spec:
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx
    livenessProbe:
      httpGet:
        path: /
        port: 80
      initialDelaySeconds: 5
      periodSeconds: 10
Important Fields

initialDelaySeconds → Time before the first health check

periodSeconds → Time interval between checks

2. Readiness Probe

A Readiness Probe checks whether the container is ready to receive user traffic.

If the container is not ready, Kubernetes removes the pod from the Service, so no traffic is sent to it.

Example YAML
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: readiness-pod
spec:
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx
    readinessProbe:
      httpGet:
        path: /
        port: 80
      initialDelaySeconds: 5
      periodSeconds: 10
3. Startup Probe

A Startup Probe is used for applications that take a long time to start.

It allows the application to start completely before Kubernetes begins health checks.

After the startup probe succeeds, the liveness probe starts working.

Example YAML
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: startup-pod
spec:
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx
    startupProbe:
      httpGet:
        path: /
        port: 80
      failureThreshold: 30
      periodSeconds: 10
CrashLoopBackOff Error

CrashLoopBackOff is a common Kubernetes error.

It occurs when a container repeatedly crashes and Kubernetes keeps restarting it.

Possible Causes

Application crash

Incorrect configuration

Liveness probe failure

Wrong port or path in configuration

Application takes too long to start

If the container fails multiple times, Kubernetes shows the CrashLoopBackOff status.

Commands to Troubleshoot CrashLoopBackOff
Check Pods
kubectl get pods
Describe Pod
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>

Example

kubectl describe pod liveness-pod
Check Logs
kubectl logs <pod-name>

Example

kubectl logs liveness-pod
Delete Pod
kubectl delete pod <pod-name>
Kubernetes Commands
Apply YAML files
kubectl apply -f liv.yml
kubectl apply -f red.yml
kubectl apply -f svc.yml
Check Pods
kubectl get pods
Check Services
kubectl get svc
Difference Between Probes
Probe	Purpose
Liveness Probe	Checks if the container is alive
Readiness Probe	Checks if the container is ready to serve traffic
Startup Probe	Checks if the application has started
Simple Flow

User sends request to Service

Service forwards request to Pod

Readiness Probe checks if the pod is ready

Liveness Probe checks if the container is alive

If the container fails, Kubernetes restarts it
